You can use `sscanf` for getting both operator and any-digit number. You can use it as follows:

```
int sum, len;
sscanf(buffer, &quot;%d%n&quot;, &amp;sum, &amp;len); // get the first number

int number;
char op;

buffer += len;

// then pattern is: &quot;operation&quot;&quot;number&quot;
while(sscanf(buffer, &quot;%c%d&quot;, &amp;op, &amp;number) == 2) // while you can scan both operation and number
{
    if (op == &#39;+&#39;)
        sum += number;
    else if (op == &#39;-&#39;)
        sum -= number;
    ...
}
```

More about sscanf [here][1].


  [1]: https://www.tutorialspoint.com/c_standard_library/c_function_sscanf.htm

Your problem, I think, is that you are doing things like

    value1 = atoi(&amp;buffer[i]);
    if (buffer[i + 1] == &#39;+&#39;)
        ...

In this fragment, the index `i` &quot;points at&quot; the spot in `buffer` where you&#39;re currently parsing.  You believe (and correctly so) that `i` &quot;points at&quot; the first of one or more digit characters.  You call `atoi` to convert that/those digit(s) to an actual integer.  All right so far.  But then you test `buffer[i + 1]` to see if there&#39;s an operator character after the number.  *That&#39;s* where the improper assumption arose, that numbers are always one digit long.  That&#39;s what you need to fix in order to correctly handle multi-digit numbers.

The best way to fix this, I&#39;d say, would be to use `strtol` instead of `atoi`.  The most obvious different between `atoi` and `strtol` is that `strtol` tells you how far it went, how many digits it used.  It does this by returning to you a pointer to the first character it didn&#39;t use.

This means, though, that to use `strtol` you&#39;re going to have to explicitly use pointers.  It will be much easier if you use a pointer

    char *p;

to step through `buffer`, rather than an index `i`.  But then you can say things like

    char *endp;
    value1 = strtol(p, &amp;endp, 10);
    p = endp;
    if (*p == &#39;+&#39;)
        ...

The way this works is, `strtol` sets `endp` to point to the first character it didn&#39;t use.  That&#39;s where you want to continue your parse, so you set `p` to `endp` and proceed.

What actually happens here is that `strtol` accepts a *pointer to a pointer*.  If you&#39;re not comfortable working with pointers yet, you may really not be ready to think about pointers to pointers, but trust me, this works.

